  "prompt": "Is there a way to for my Google Calendar to manage my Office 365 Exchange Cal that doesn't involve using the Subscribe Option?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several ways to manage your Office 365 Exchange Calendar with Google Calendar without using the \"Subscribe\" option. Here are a few methods you can consider:\n\n1. **Third-Party Integration Tools**: \n   - Tools like \"Zapier\" or \"Integromat\" (now Make) can automate syncing between your Google Calendar and Office 365 Calendar. You can create specific workflows or \"zaps\" to ensure that events created or updated in one calendar are mirrored in the other.\n   \n2. **Microsoft Power Automate**:\n   - Previously known as Microsoft Flow, Power Automate allows you to create automated workflows between your apps and services. You can set up a flow that syncs events between your Office 365 and Google Calendar.\n\n3. **Calendar Sync Tools**:\n   - There are dedicated calendar sync applications such as \"Sync2\" or \"CalendarBridge\" that can offer two-way sync between Google Calendar and Office 365. These tools often provide more robust features but might come with a cost.\n\n4. **Outlook Desktop Application**:\n   - If you are using Outlook on your desktop, you can add your Google Account to Outlook. This way, both calendars appear in Outlook, and you can manage them from there. Note that this method doesn\u2019t sync the calendars but lets you view and manage them together.\n\n5. **Mobile Apps**:\n   - Some mobile calendar apps support viewing and managing both Google and Office 365 calendars in one place, though syncing may not always be supported.\n\nBefore using any third-party tool, make sure to check its compatibility with your systems and read reviews to ensure it meets your needs for syncing and managing the calendars efficiently.",
